; sub - The SUB Hacking & Info Tool (Raw Hex / Intel HEX format)
; Author: Subhobhai (subhobhai943)
; GitHub: https://github.com/subhobhai943
;
; This file documents the raw bytes of the "sub banner" output string
; encoded in Intel HEX format (commonly used in embedded/firmware tools).
;
; The hex data below encodes the ASCII bytes of the SUB banner string.
; You can flash this to a microcontroller UART TX buffer to have it
; print the SUB banner on boot.
;
; Decoded string (ASCII):
;   \n  +-+-+-+\n  |S|U|B|\n  +-+-+-+\n  by Subhobhai\n
;
; Intel HEX format:
;   :LLAAAATT[DD...]CC
;   LL = byte count, AAAA = address, TT = record type, DD = data, CC = checksum
;
; Record type 00 = data, 01 = end-of-file

; Address 0x0000: "\n  +-+-+-+\n  |S|U|B|\n  +-+-+-+\n"
:200000000A20202B2D2B2D2B2D2B0A20207C537C557C427C0A20202B2D2B2D2B2D2B0A00BE

; Address 0x0020: "  by Subhobhai | github.com/subhobhai943\n"
:2800200020206279205375626F626861692020207C2067697468756220636F6D2F7375626F6268616939343380

; End of file record
:00000001FF

; --- How to use ---
; 1. Decode with: python3 -c "
im;    import binascii
;    # Parse the hex data bytes from lines above and decode to ASCII
; "
;
; 2. Or use `objcopy` / `avrdude` to flash to an AVR/ARM microcontroller.
;
; 3. Quick decode (Python one-liner for the banner bytes):
;    python3 -c "print(bytes.fromhex('0A20202B2D2B2D2B2D2B0A20207C537C557C427C0A20202B2D2B2D2B2D2B0A').decode())"
